Special flights to the eye of the storm

By zhijie Yang

PUBLISHED: March 16,2020

Captain Gu Zhenyu received the mission call notice, less than 6 hours from the plane took off.

In his 27 years behind the wheel, that was rare. He became a flight cadet in 1993 and was promoted from co-pilot of Air China to captain at the end of 1999. Flights are usually scheduled 72 hours in advance, and this is limited to familiar airports and familiar routes.

Hang up the phone, this is the third day of the New Year more than two o'clock in the afternoon, Gu Zhenyu immediately drove to the airport. At 4 p.m. , the three crew members arrived at the rendezvous point, changed their uniforms, got their equipment, and took their temperature. Gu Zhenyu still had no flight plan, this means: "which plane to fly? The weight of the cargo? The volume? All unknown. "

The only thing that was clear was that, more than three hours later, as captain, Gu would most likely have to fly an Airbus A330, a 150-person Beijing medical team, to Wuhan, the city with the worst case of new crown pneumonia. "very likely" , because there is another plane and a crew, crew, and Gu Zhenyu in the same preparation.

It seems to defy the rules of civil aviation —— that flights go according to plan, with airlines planning their flights well in advance and organizing people to follow them. Even when faced with rain or snow weather or large-scale flow control, flight delays, the airline's response has a set of specific procedures.

But the sudden outbreak of new crown disease before the Spring Festival, so that many of the civil aviation work has become unpredictable. On January 23, in order to block the spread of the epidemic, the city of Wuhan was closed, the airport, railway station and other channels from the Han Dynasty were closed. Subsequently, several countries suspended flights to and from China. Within a month, more than 3,000 flights involving Wuhan were cancelled by Air China alone. But at the same time, medical teams and rescue and protection materials still need to be continuously imported into Wuhan, to ensure the unimpeded lifeline. At particular times, these special flights have played a special role as one of the few routes to the eye of the storm.

Six-hour emergency standby

"The third batch of medical teams will leave today, with about 150 people and unknown supplies, " Han Jingyan, the party secretary of the China Shipping Control Center, told China News Weekly, the NMHC and the Civil Aviation Administration of China have issued directives to several domestic airlines to carry out emergency medical support charter flights. At 10:35 a.m. on the third day of the Lunar New Year, Air China Flight CA041 had just delivered the second batch of medical teams from Beijing to Wuhan. Not long after that, the Air China Shipping Control Center received a new task.

Operation Control Center is the Central Department to organize the operation of aircraft. Given the uncertainty over medical supplies, the operations center deployed an Airbus A330 and a Boeing 737 within two hours, while standing by to avoid a temporary change of aircraft.

Gu Zhenyu has been flying the Airbus A330 since 2006, a wide body passenger plane that can carry passengers and cargo far beyond the narrow body. It flies mainly on intercontinental routes and the main route between Beijing, Shanghai and Guangzhou, and rarely carries out domestic flights to Wuhan. "We are continuing to monitor the situation in Wuhan, and medical teams from all over the country are going to Wuhan to support us. Based on the number of people and medical equipment, it is only a matter of time before a wide-body machine is used, " Gu told China news weekly.

He did not tell his family to fly to Wuhan, lest they worry, but simply explained, "normal overtime. ".

At 4 p.m. on Jan. 27, four trucks loaded with masks, protective clothing and other medical supplies arrived at the Capital International Airport. The material is larger than the Boeing 737's cargo hold, and, as Gu predicted, the Airbus A330 is on the scene.

At 5 p.m. , the captain, Gu Zhenyu, and two other crew members boarded the plane for a routine inspection. Until now, they had not been able to get an accurate count of the number of passengers and the weight of goods -- a number that Gu was eager to know.

"from an epidemic prevention perspective, we should stay in Wuhan as short as possible and have as few people as possible, " Gu said, adding that the requirement for the crew was that the plane should have enough fuel to support its return journey. The amount of fuel needed to make a round trip can be calculated, but only if you know the weight of the people and cargo on board, "If there is too much fuel, the plane may land at Wuhan Airport overweight, which may affect safety. This mission must not have any safety problems. If there are less fuel belts, you must refuel in Wuhan. If you want to contact people, you will have the problem of epidemic prevention on the spot. "

Operation Control Center as a "brain" , need to consider more issues. "If the plane flies to Wuhan, what if it breaks down temporarily? What if the weather in Wuhan is bad and we need to prepare for a landing? We all have to work out the corresponding plan, and it can't be the same as normal flights,"Kong Jianrong, senior manager of the Operation Control Center's General Duty Room, told China News Weekly, they also have to prepare other plans, for example, if a sudden rainstorm or snow in Wuhan, the plane can not be prepared to land at the airport in Hubei, then they must return to Beijing, in order to ensure timely support.

The transportation of epidemic prevention materials is also different from the past. Air Transport Cargo Weight and volume have related requirements, but this shipment of anti-epidemic materials are mostly protective clothing and face masks, light weight but large volume, cargo hold simply can not fit, only part of the materials placed in the passenger cabin. Han Jingyan said that with the approval of the Civil Aviation Administration, special flights can be special operations, they will be tied up with materials, fasten seat belts and other methods fixed in the seat.

More than 8 pm, 30 minutes before take-off, Gu Zhenyu finally got the aircraft carrier data, including passengers, material weight, according to adjust the aircraft fuel. At 8:47 pm, CA043, a large flight crew of Air China Flight Group, Gu Zhenyu, Wen Jun and Yuan Bin, took off from Beijing Capital International Airport for Wuhan, carrying 150 medical personnel and more than 13 tons of medical supplies.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
On January 27, Air China's Eighth Disaster Relief Charter plane flew to Wuhan. Photo / interviewees

"It is a great honor to be able to transport medical personnel and supplies to the Wuhan Epidemic area during this special period, " Gu Zhenyu said in a radio broadcast before takeoff. Shortly after, tens of thousands of feet in the air sounded another sound, let Gu Zhenyu feel warm. Tower controllers found the special flight from the flight number "code" and, after sending instructions, said an unusual "thank you" to CA043. In the same area, other aircraft in flight also sent greetings to the special flight, "thank you, Wuhan Refueling! "

Two days'worth of international flights

On the afternoon of February 3, the Air China Shipping Control Center received a clear notice: two days later, Air China needs to send a plane to Osaka, Japan, where it will detain 223 passengers from Hubei Province, as well as nearly 2.5 tons of epidemic prevention materials donated by various circles of Japanese society and overseas Chinese, they were shipped back to Wuhan together.

Received the notice, Air China Osaka business department has closed, leaving the airline only one day to prepare. The Operations Center, which is responsible for the unified deployment, has to work out a flight plan overnight. Han said the operations center first determined the type of aircraft, "by the A330-300 aircraft, Air China has no capacity in Ōsaka, need to deploy a plane from headquarters, fly from Beijing to Ōsaka, then fly to Wuhan. "

But the first problem that Operation Control Center encounters is, the medical staff that the 2 health that must be provided on the plane assigns to go, whether have Japanese visa? With the flight leaving in a day and no time to apply for a temporary visa, the Transportation Control Center decided to charter a flight from Beijing to Ōsaka, leaving no visa issue for medical staff until they disembarked.

Adding an international flight isn't easy. Operations Control Center to determine air routes as soon as possible, to fly which way is more appropriate, involving overflight countries, airlines need to apply for special. Beijing will fly to Ōsaka through South Korea, they have to calculate in advance the time and place of entry and exit in South Korea, which route to take, a day in advance with the South Korean civil aviation authorities to apply. All this work had to be done in a day on the 4th. And by normal procedure, to add an international flight, the airline needs to apply at least one and a half months in advance, in a specific period.

February 4 local time at 9:00 am, Air China Osaka Business Manager Bai Ge got the flight plan. Within a day, they have to apply to Osaka Kansai airport landing time flight clearance, coordination with the airport departments of airport security, organize stranded passengers purchase tickets. In addition, they had to apply to the Ministry of Land, Infrastructure, Transport and Tourism for permission to fly, "several departments are working at the same time, we are like a war. "

That afternoon, from the South Korean Civil Aviation Department off-duty only 1 hour, Beijing's operation and Control Center has not been approved. Han Jingyan and through the local business department and emergency contact with South Korea, in the last half an hour before work was successfully approved, "a stone fell to the ground. ".

At 11:00 on February 5, Kansai International Airport arrived to find the place well prepared. In order to completely separate the group from the rest of the passengers, the airport placed the flights in a separate business terminal in Terminal T2. The tourists, from Hubei Province, would be another disaster if they caught an infection while waiting for a flight, so they would need to be rigorously screened. Each passenger is required to have his or her temperature taken and to declare whether he or she has left Hubei for more than 14 days, with a limit of 14 days for separate accommodation. To avoid the risk of cross-infection on the plane, all passengers have to eat before boarding.

You Teng is the Air China Beijing Cabin senior manager, participates in this flight support mission. Before arriving in Ōsaka, the flight crew, safety staff and eight flight attendants were asked to change into protective clothing. Yuteng also had some concerns at first, this will not bring panic to the passengers, but did not think, the passengers have a stronger sense of self-defense.

Yu Teng's first passengers were a family of four, all wearing protective clothing, wrapped tightly, he was stunned, a moment did not know whether staff or passengers. He was impressed by the situation: "The passengers were divided into two factions, one very professional, wearing protective clothing; the other faction was a folk faction, wearing a raincoat, wearing goggles, a plastic bag on the soles of their feet. So, instead, if we don't wear them, they might question us."

Tight "command center"

As of March 9, CNAC has carried out a total of 47 rescue and transport charter flights, using charter flights to transport 4,546 medical personnel, 430 returned overseas compatriots, and nearly 404 tons of epidemic prevention materials; and using normal flights and cargo flights for 1,634 flights, 2,457 tons of supplies.

After Wuhan closes a city, what should do in the next three days? Which flights will be affected in the future when flight volumes are sure to plummet? Operations centers need to develop follow-up procedures. Kong Jianrong experienced the SARS epidemic in 2003, but now many mechanisms and procedures are completely different and flight volume is not at the same level. In 2003, he remembers, Air China had only about 400 flights a day; today it has 1,400.

Han Jingyan said the outbreak has indeed had a relatively big impact on the aviation industry. "Last year, there were about 53,000 flights operated by Air China during the Spring Festival travel season. This year, we have only 35,000 flights operated during the Spring Festival travel season, a sharp drop of 40 percent. " In addition, according to Air China, between the closure of Wuhan and March 6, Air China cancelled 4,010 flights in the Hubei region and 3,664 in Wuhan.

Flights have been cancelled, but the workload at the operations centre is increasing. As the airline internal coordination, command department, Operations and Control Center not only need to grasp the progress of the epidemic, coordination department is far beyond the scope of the past. "In the past, we may only communicate with the Civil Aviation Administration, the Air Traffic Control Bureau and the airports, but now we have to communicate with the customs and Quarantine, the Health Commission and even foreign government departments. They didn't involve these channels, there is no corresponding process, now they are just fumbling to do it, and then establish the corresponding system,"Kong said.

On February 1st Vietnam's aviation authority announced that all flights between Vietnam and China would be closed from 1300 hours. The news came as a surprise to many airlines.

At 16:00 p.m. that day, an Air China flight was due to fly home from Vietnam, and passengers had even arrived at the airport. At 20:00 that night, Air China had another flight coming back. Upon receipt of the notification, the airline was required to ground flights only under the rules of the other side, which meant that many of Air China's passengers would be stranded there.

"Many countries in Southeast Asia can sign on the ground, and tourists usually come back after only a few days. At this time, when flights are cut off, and they don't have visas, where else can they go? " Kong admitted, the airline was also worried. "these are our compatriots. They don't know anyone there. ".

Air China Business Department immediately and Vietnam Civil Aviation Bureau for consultations, finally found a disguised compromise, send air passengers back, as far as possible to reduce the risk of disconnection. "This kind of emergency situation is quite common, and operators also need to keep track of which countries have imposed restrictions on flights, " Kong said, adding that during the outbreak, the entire China Shipping Control Center was under constant strain. Sometimes, just after work, temporary things need to be coordinated, but also immediately back to work.

"If we die on our own, we can not coordinate, which is the guarantee of the whole system, " Kong said. "It was not Air China alone, but the regional administrations, the Air Traffic Control Bureau and the entire Civil Aviation Administration. "

As of March 6,29 domestic airlines had carried out 413 missions during the outbreak, transporting 36,700 personnel and 2,630.7 tons of supplies, according to the Civil Aviation Administration of China. Of this total, 302 sorties were carried out by medical teams, with 33,800 medical and other rescue personnel; 13 sorties were carried out to retrieve stranded passengers and 1,647 returned passengers; and 87 sorties were carried out to transport supplies, including 39 sorties from overseas. These flights became a special "lifeline" during the outbreak.
